	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65023247"><p>Sometimes, I wonder if we should consider algorithm cascades.  No, unlike the novice belief that two 256 algorithms will give 512 bits of security, (at best, they give 257 bits), this is intended to deal with an algorithm being completely broken.  For example, if we did RSA, ED-25519, and Khyber, or ED25519, Khyber and SPINCS/XMSS, algorithms that use hashes and lattices, as well as a good old factoring standard, we should have solid protection via conventional attacks, as well as quantum attacks.</p><p>Or more si<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

