			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65022843" name="comment_link_65022843" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23555181&amp;cid=65022843" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65022843)" >x509 certs are already insecure - attack vector</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65022843" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65022843); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~FeelGood314">FeelGood314</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~FeelGood314">( 2516288 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65022843"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65022843">x509 certs are written in ASN1.  ASN1 is like (type, length, value) triplets on steroids.  They are nested many layers deep and the length value can be set to variable.  Most people think parsing them is straight forward but if the lengths of the nested elements don't match the length of the parent's most parsers have at least one instance where they won't catch the problem.  Worse, for well crafted ASN1, this can be exploited such that different parsers will parse it differently.  This means I can submit a</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65022843">

</div>
</div>

